Whitwam, 2023 Best in Show winner at SOMI Art Fest (formerly known as the South Miami Rotary Art Festival)! \ud83c\udf1f Dive into his captivating landscapes that celebrate the beauty of natural Florida. From serene river scenes to lush, hidden springs and their denizens, Curtis's work invites you to explore the wonders of our environment. Don't miss the chance to see his latest creations and experience the magic firsthand at this year's SOMI Art Fest. Join us on February 24-25, 2024, and let Curtis's art inspire your next adventure! \ud83c\udfa8\ud83c\udf43\n\n\ud83d\udd52 Join us from 10 AM to 6 PM on Saturday and 10 AM to 5 PM on Sunday. \n\n\ud83c\udfb7\ud83c\udfb6 Don\u2019t miss our live music performances throughout the festival, and stay later on Saturday until 9:00 PM for music and dancing on Saturday at the Stella Artois Beer Garden!\n\n\ud83d\udc3e And yes, we\u2019re dog-friendly too! Bring your furry friends along to enjoy our special dog hydration station and vendors.\n\n\ud83c\udf9f\ufe0f Admission is free, with plenty of nearby parking. Take the Metrorail to the South Miami station and celebrate art, community, and family at SOMI Art Fest 2024!\n\nPresented by \u0040unitedcommunitybank. Jewelry\n\nCongratulations to Melissa Hampton on winning Second in Show! We thank her for being a part of our show, for her kind words about the festival, and sharing her inspiration and special technique of gold flow with us! \n\nMore about Melissa:\nArtist and metalsmith Melissa Hampton launched Ascendant Jewelry Studio in August 2019. Although she has been making jewelry for decades, she took time after graduate school to build her business while working full time in the nonprofit sector. Born and raised outside of St. Louis, MO, Melissa became fascinated with jewelry and the idea of adornment after inheriting her grandmother\u2019s collection of vintage costume jewelry as a young girl. She went on to explore this field and in 2015 earned a Masters in Fine Arts: Studio Art from Southern Illinois University, Edwardsville where she majored in Metals and Jewelry Design. She uses a variety of traditional and unconventional metalsmithing techniques to express big ideas in the form of wearable sculpture. \n\nPlease visit her website and follow her on her socials to support her stunning work. Her next round of shows is out west, in Bonita Springs.
